"Wang N.","Decrease trend of dust event frequency over the past 200 years recorded in the Malan ice core from the northern Tibetan Plateau",2005,"Chinese Science Bulletin","50","24",,"2866","2871",,,10.1360/982005-237,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33749477494&partnerID=40&md5=0be0ea9dc266ce6f8b2cc4264fb17676","Key Laboratory of Cryosphere and Environment, Cold and Arid Regions Environmental and Engineering Research Institute, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Lanzhou 73000, China; Institute of Tibetan Plateau Research, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100085, China","Wang, N., Key Laboratory of Cryosphere and Environment, Cold and Arid Regions Environmental and Engineering Research Institute, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Lanzhou 73000, China, Institute of Tibetan Plateau Research, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100085, China","By analyses of the dust layers in the Malan ice core from the northern Tibetan Plateau, it was found that dirty ratio in this core might be a good proxy for dust event frequency. The variations in the dirty ratio displayed a decrease trend over the past 200 years, which implies that dust events became less frequent during the study period. The decrease trend in the variations in dust event frequency might be caused mostly by the natural processes, including increasing precipitation and weakening westerly which might be related with global wanning. Furthermore, significant negative correlation was found between the dirty ratio and δ18O in the Malan ice core. This is highly important for studying the effect of atmospheric dust on climate change.","Climate change; Dust event; Malan ice core; Tibetan plateau",,,,,,,"Prospero, J.M., Long-range transport of mineral dust in the global atmosphere: Impact of African dust on the environment of the southeastern United States (1999) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 96 (7), pp. 3396-3403; Uno, I., Amano, H., Emori, S., Trans-Pacific yellow sand transport observed in April 1998: A numerical simulation (2001) Journal of Geophysical Research, 106 (D16), pp. 18331-18341; Grousset, F.E., Ginoux, P., Bory, A., Case study of a Chinese dust plume reaching the French Alps (2003) Geophysical Research Letters, 30 (6), p. 1277. , doi: 10.1029/2002GL016833; Bory, A.J.M., Biscaye, P.E., Grousset, F.E., Two distinct seasonal Asian source regions for mineral dust deposited in Greenland (NorthGRIP) (2003) Geophysical Research Letters, 30 (4), p. 1167. , doi: 10.1029/2002GL016446; Fraser, R.S., Kaufman, Y.J., The relative importance of aerosol scattering and absorption in remote sensing (1985) IEEE Transactions on Geoscience and Remote Sensing, 23, pp. 625-633; Sokolik, I.N., Toon, O.B., Direct radiative forcing by anthropogenic airborne mineral aerosol (1996) Nature, 381, pp. 681-683; Alpert, P., Kaufman, Y.J., Shay-El, Y., Quantification of dust-forced heating of the lower troposphere (1998) Nature, 395 (6700), pp. 367-370; Satheesh, S.K., Ramanathan, V., Large differences in tropical aerosol forcing at the top of the atmosphere and Earth's surface (2000) Nature, 405 (6782), pp. 60-63; Kaufman, Y.J., Tanré, D., Dubovik, O., Absorption of sunlight by dust as inferred from satellite and ground-based remote sensing (2001) Geophysical Research Letters, 28 (8), pp. 1479-1482; Kinne, S., Pueschel, R., Aerosol radiative forcing for Asian continental outflow (2001) Atmospheric Environment, 35 (30), pp. 5019-5028; Rosenfeld, D., Rudich, Y., Lahav, R., Desert dust suppressing precipitation: A possible desertification feedback loop (2001) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 98 (11), pp. 5975-5980; Ramanathan, V., Crutzen, P.J., Kiehl, J.T., Aerosols, climate, and the hydrological cycle (2001) Science, 294 (5549), pp. 2119-2124; Kaufman, Y.J., Tanré, D., Boucher, O., A satellite view of aerosols in the climate system (2002) Nature, 419 (6903), pp. 215-223; Mahowald, N.M., Kieh